MDC Partners, Inc. – Value Analysis (NASDAQ:MDCA) : January 24, 2017 – CapitalCube








































Skip to content





CapitalCube





















MDC Partners, Inc. – Value Analysis (NASDAQ:MDCA) : January 24, 2017 
January 24, 2017 by CapitalCube 


Click here to see latest analysis
Capitalcube gives MDC Partners, Inc. a score of 22.
Our analysis is based on comparing MDC Partners, Inc. with the following peers – Interpublic Group of Companies, Inc., Omnicom Group Inc, National CineMedia, Inc., Harte-Hanks, Inc. and Publicis Groupe SA Sponsored ADR (IPG-US, OMC-US, NCMI-US, HHS-US and PUBGY-US).
Investment Outlook
MDC Partners, Inc. has a fundamental score of 22 and has a relative valuation of UNDERVALUED. 

Access our research and ratings on MDC Partners, Inc.
Sign Up


Company Overview

From a peer analysis angle, relative underperformance over the last year has improved more recently.


MDC Partners Inc. Class A currently has a negative book value and its current Price/Assets ratio of 0.20 is lower than its peer median (0.68).


MDCA-US‘s book value of equity is not positive and suggests that that it is not meaningful to analyze its ROE versus P/E in order to determine whether the company has an operating or growth advantage.


MDCA-US has relatively low profit margins and median asset efficiency.


Changes in annual revenues (relative to peers) are better than the change in its earnings (relative to peers), implying the company is focused more on revenues.


MDCA-US‘s return on assets currently and over the past five years has trailed the peer median and suggests the company might be operationally challenged relative to its peers.


Company appears to give away relatively high gross margins to relatively high operating costs suggesting a differentiated product portfolio with low pre-tax margins relative to peers.


While MDCA-US‘s revenue growth in recent years has been above the peer median, the stock’s Price/EBITDA ratio is less than the peer median suggesting that the company’s earnings may be peaking and the market expects a decline in its growth expectations.


The company seems to be over-investing in a business with median returns.


MDCA-US seems too levered to raise additional debt.

Access our research and ratings on MDC Partners, Inc.
Sign Up



Leverage & Liquidity
MDCA-US would seem to have a hard time raising additional debt.

With debt at a relatively high 60.23% of its enterprise value compared to an overall benchmark of 25% (Note: The peer median is currently 30.97%), and relatively tight interest coverage level of 1.81x, MDCA-US would have a hard time raising much additional debt. The company has a Constrained profile in terms of its ability to take on further debt.


All 5 peers for the company have an outstanding debt balance.

MDCA-US has moved to a Limited Flexibility from a relatively high leverage profile at the recent year-end.

MDCA-US‘s interest coverage has declined 0.76 points from last year’s high but remains above its five-year average interest coverage of 0.68.


The decrease in its interest coverage to 1.81x from 2.57x (in 2015) was also accompanied by a decrease in its peer median during this period to 6.21x from 7.54x.


Interest coverage rose 0.56 points relative to peers. It is also below the 2.50x coverage benchmark unlike the peer median.


MDCA-US‘s debt-EV is its highest relative to the last five years and compares to a low of 32.97% in 2013.


The increase in its debt-EV to 60.23% from 41.11% (in 2015) was also accompanied by an increase in its peer median during this period to 30.97% from 26.10%.


Relative to peers, debt-EV rose 14.25 percentage points.

